"Popov D.","An option for solar thermal repowering of fossil fuel fired power plants",2011,"Solar Energy","85","2",,"344","349",,,10.1016/j.solener.2010.11.017,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78651352242&partnerID=40&md5=679fa55e4474012434a166ccd62728c4","Technical University of Sofia, Thermal and Nuclear Power Engineering Department, Kliment Ohridski, 8, bl. 2, EMF, 1000 Sofia, Bulgaria","Popov, D., Technical University of Sofia, Thermal and Nuclear Power Engineering Department, Kliment Ohridski, 8, bl. 2, EMF, 1000 Sofia, Bulgaria","Global climate change urges immediate measures to be taken to limit greenhouse gas emission coming from the fossil fuel fired power plants. Solar thermal energy can be involved in different ways in existing power generation plants in order to replace heat produced by fossil fuels. Solar field feed water preheating is mainly discussed in this paper as an option for fast and feasible RES penetration. Rankine regenerative steam cycled power plant has been modelled with Thermoflow software. The plant model incorporates also a field with solar Fresnel collectors that directly heats boiler's feed water. The proposed plant modification yields substantial fossil fuel input reduction. The best results can be obtained when the group of high pressure heaters is replaced and feed water temperature exceeds its original design value. The solar power generation share can reach up to 23% of the power plant capacity in this case, having efficiency higher than 39% for the best solar hour of the year. © 2010 Elsevier Ltd.","Fossil fuels; Fresnel collectors; High pressure heaters; Rankine regenerative cycle; Repowering; Solar thermal power","Fresnel; High pressure; Rankine; Repowering; Solar thermal power; Flow of water; Fossil fuel power plants; Fossil fuels; Gas emissions; Gas plants; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Solar heating; Solar power generation; Steam power plants; Solar energy; climate change; emission control; fossil fuel; greenhouse gas; high pressure; measurement method; numerical model; power generation; power plant; software; solar power; water temperature",,,,,,"Aringhoff, R., Geyer, M., Herrmann, U., Kistner, R., Nava, P., Osuna, R., (2002), pp. 37-42. , AndaSol - 50MW solar plants with 9hour storage for southern Spain. In: Proceedings of 11th SolarPACES International Symposium, Zurich, Switzerland, 4-6 September 2002Bockamp, S., Griestop, T., Fruth, M., Ewert, M., Lerchenmüller, H., Mertins, M., Morin, G., Dersch, J., (2003), http://www.solarec-egypt.com, Solar thermal power generation. Presented at Power-Gen Europe 2003, Düsseldorf, GermanyGriffin, P., Huschka, K., Morin, G., Software for design, simulation and cost estimation of solar thermal power and heat cycles (2009) Proceedings of the SolarPACES 2009 Conference in Berlin, , http://www.thermoflow.com, Germany; Häberle, A., Zahler, C., Lerchenmüller, H., Mertins, M., Wittwer, C., Trieb, F., Dersch, J., The Solarmundo line focussing Fresnel collector. Optical and thermal performance and cost calculations (2002) Proceedings of 11th SolarPACES International Symposium, , http://www.ise.fraunhofer.de, 4-6 September 2002, Zurich, Switzerland. </v; Hu, E., Yang, Y., Nishimura, A., Yilmaz, F., Kouzani, A., (2009) Solar thermal aided power generation, , http://www.sciencedirect.com, Applied Energy. </science?_ob=ArticleURL&_udi=B6V1T-4XSSV3S-1&_user=3738940&_coverDate=11%2F25%2F2009&_rdoc=1&_fmt=high&_orig=search&_sort=d&_; Hu, E.J., Mills, D., Morrison, G., Lievre, P., Solar power boosting of fossil fuelled power plant (2003) Proceedings ISES 2003, , http://solar1.mech.unsw.edu.au, Göteborg, June 14-19, 2003. </glm/papers/HU_ISES2003_O5_24.pdf>; Mills, D., Morrison, G.L., Compact linear Fresnel reflector solar thermal power plants (1999) Solar Energy, 68, pp. 263-283; Mills, D., Advances in solar thermal electricity technology (2004) Solar Energy, 76 (1-3), pp. 19-31. , http://www.sciencedirect.com/science?_ob=ArticleURL&_udi=B